{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/hirsutism/background-information/causes/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"7c04b952-69e3-54ba-abf5-964402df757c","slug":"causes","fullItemName":"Causes","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 71a07179-9288-47e1-9de7-847c5f4ceed0 --><h2>What causes it?</h2><!-- end field 71a07179-9288-47e1-9de7-847c5f4ceed0 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item d874ec80-555b-4c53-8506-7a5bc12f0da3 --><!-- begin field d01ac353-d628-494c-8fec-f4517fc410cb --><ul><li><strong>Polycystic ovary syndrome </strong>is the most common cause of hirsutism (more than 70% of cases) [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hirsutism/references/\">Rothman and Wierman, 2011</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hirsutism/references/\">Lui et al, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hirsutism/references/\">Kini and Ramalingam, 2018</a>]. </li><li><strong>Idiopathic hirsutism </strong>(a diagnosis of exclusion where there is no apparent underlying cause, normal serum androgen concentrations, normal ovulatory and menstrual cycles, and normal ovarian morphology) is also common, accounting for around half of women with mild hirsutism. Idiopathic hirsutism may be a result of increased sensitivity to androgens in the pilosebaceous unit, enhanced local conversion of testosterone to dihydrotestosterone by 5-alpha-reductase, or altered function of androgen receptors [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hirsutism/references/\">Blume-Peytavi et al, 2012</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hirsutism/references/\">Mihailidis et al, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hirsutism/references/\">BMJ Best Practice, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hirsutism/references/\">Kini and Ramalingam, 2018</a>]. </li><li><strong>Less commonly, hirsutism may be caused by </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hirsutism/references/\">Rothman and Wierman, 2011</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hirsutism/references/\">Escobar-Morreale et al, 2012</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hirsutism/references/\">Lui et al, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hirsutism/references/\">Kini and Ramalingam, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hirsutism/references/\">Matheson and Bain, 2019</a>]<strong>:</strong><ul><li>Non-classical congenital adrenal hyperplasia.</li><li>Androgen-secreting tumour. </li><li>Cushing's syndrome.</li><li>Acromegaly.</li><li>Hyperprolactinaemia.</li><li>Thyroid disorders.</li><li>Drugs (for example anabolic steroids, ciclosporin, danazol,  phenytoin, sodium valproate, and tamoxifen). </li></ul></li><li><strong>In menopausal women, </strong>reduction in oestrogen and progesterone production can result in hair and skin disorders. The reduction in progesterone can increase the influence of androgens on the sebaceous glands and hair follicles [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/hirsutism/references/\">Blume-Peytavi et al, 2012</a>].</li></ul><!-- end field d01ac353-d628-494c-8fec-f4517fc410cb --><!-- end item d874ec80-555b-4c53-8506-7a5bc12f0da3 -->","topic":{"id":"f7bb546f-c63b-5f36-8592-742d53a300ba","topicId":"6cd0021b-eeb7-4f76-9627-4f095658d33a","topicName":"Hirsutism","slug":"hirsutism","lastRevised":"Last revised in July 2020","chapters":[{"id":"7f1b7b92-6387-5893-b9c1-1b0fe5e6921f","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"ad41ddff-180c-5c56-9fa8-cfcaa4b301ac","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"